Load the Data

There are three datasets that you will use in this project. They are similar to the datasets we had with the French data: a spatial object (county), a dataset of demographic data, and a dataset of daily Coronavirus records at the county level.

county <- read_sf(file.path("data", "us_counties.geojson"))
covid <- read_csv(file.path("data", "us_county_covid.csv"))
demog <- read_csv(file.path("data", "us_county_metadata.csv"))

The COVID-19 dataset has fewer columns than the one from France. It has only cumulative case counts and reported deaths. Note that these are only the counties with complete data from 01 April 2020.

Most of the variables should be self-explanatory. Unemployment rate is in percentages (0-100), median household income in USD. February and August average temperatures are in Celsius. The physicians_per_pop give the number of active physicians per 100k residents according to the AAMC in 2018 at the state level. Note that there is information for almost every county in the US, even if there are no records in the COVID-19 dataset.

Prompts

1. Spatial Extent

Question Show a spatial visualization (i.e., a map) of the infection rate (cases per population) in the U.S. on 1 May 2020, 15 June 2020, and 1 October for the “lower 48” states (no Hawaii, Alaska, or Puerto Rico). Also, separately show the infection rate for Hawaii on 15 June 2020. Try to describe the patterns in a few short sentences. Make sure to use appropriate projections and color scales.

county %>%
  inner_join(demog, by =c('fips','state')) %>%
  inner_join(covid, by =c('fips','state')) %>%
  filter(date == '2020-05-01') %>%
  filter(! state %in% c('HI','AK','PR')) %>%
  mutate(infection_rate = cases / population) %>%
  st_transform(3083) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = infection_rate), color = "black", size = 0.1) +
  scale_fill_distiller(trans = "log2", palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10) +
  labs(title = "Infection Rate of COVID-19 in the US", subtitle = "May 1st, 2020")

On May 1st, only a few areas in the U.S. have a high infection rate. New York City had a lot of Coronavirus cases, along with some areas in the south and the midwest.

county %>%
  inner_join(demog, by =c('fips','state')) %>%
  inner_join(covid, by =c('fips','state')) %>%
  filter(date == '2020-06-15') %>%
  filter(! state %in% c('HI','AK','PR')) %>%
  mutate(infection_rate = cases / population) %>%
  st_transform(3083) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = infection_rate), color = "black", size = 0.1) +
  scale_fill_distiller(trans = "log2", palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10) +
  labs(title = "Infection Rate of COVID-19 in the US", subtitle = "June 15th, 2020")

On June 15th, some counties that had a high infection rate in the south has spread to new counties. The Coronavirus cases have also spread further across the Northeast. Lastly, regions in Arizona and California have gotten worse and there are more emerging hotspots.

county %>%
  inner_join(demog, by =c('fips','state')) %>%
  inner_join(covid, by =c('fips','state')) %>%

On October 1st, regions in the Northeast have been successful in lowering the daily Coronavirus cases, which has led to a lower infection rate. Unfortunately for the counties in the south, infection rates have gotten worse and has spread dramatically inland.

On July 15th in Hawaii, all 4 islands had different infection rates for the Coronavirus pandemic. Honolulu, the capital of Hawaii, was the island with the worse infection rate. This might be due to how populated it is.

2. Political Party

Question How does the general political affiliation at the county level relate to the observed case fatality rate (cases / deaths) and the overall infection rate (cases / population)? Answer the question on a month-by-month basis (i.e., compute the rates for each month separately, not cumulatively) and plot these showing the change over time.

demog %>%
 mutate(is_democrat = (per_dem_2016 > .5)) %>%
 inner_join(covid, by =c('fips','state')) %>%
 mutate(day = day(date)) %>%
 filter(day == 1) %>%
 group_by(is_democrat, date) %>%
 summarize(sm_sum(cases), sm_sum(population), sm_sum(deaths)) %>%
 mutate(new_deaths = lead(deaths_sum) - deaths_sum) %>%
 mutate(new_cases = lead(cases_sum) - cases_sum) %>%
 mutate(fatality_rate = new_deaths / new_cases) %>%
 mutate(infection_rate = new_cases / population_sum) %>%
 ggplot() +
 geom_line(aes(date, fatality_rate, color = is_democrat)) +
 scale_color_manual(labels = c("Republican", "Democrat"), values = c("red", "blue")) +
 scale_x_date(date_breaks = "month", date_minor_breaks = "month", date_labels = "%B") +
 labs(title = "Fatality Rate for Conservative and Liberal Counties", x = "Date", y = "Fatality Rate", color = "Political Affiliation")
## Warning: Removed 2 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

3. Largest Counties

Question Visualize the number of new cases in the 10 largest counties over the time range of the entire dataset for each day using a 7-day moving average.

covid %>%
  inner_join(demog, by= c('fips', 'state')) %>%
  arrange(desc(population)) %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  slice(1:8) %>%
  group_by(county) %>%
  mutate(cases_new = cases - lag(cases)) %>%
  mutate(cases_new7 = roll_meanr(cases_new, n = 7)) %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x = date, y = cases_new7, color = county)) +
  labs(title = "New Cases for the 8 Largest Counties", subtitle = "7-day Moving Average", x = "Date",
      y = "7 Day Rolling Average", color = "County")

4. Population Density

Question Compute the population density of each county. Group the counties into 5 groups based on their population density and compute the overall fatality rate (cases / deaths), infection rate (cases / population) and mortality rate (deaths / cases) for each group on 1 October.

county %>%
  left_join(demog, by = c("fips", "state")) %>%
  mutate(area = as.numeric(set_units(st_area(geometry), "km^2"))) %>%
  mutate(density = population / area) %>%
  mutate(bucket = cut(log2(density + 1), breaks = 5, labels = FALSE)) %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  inner_join(covid, by= c('fips', 'state')) %>%
  filter(date == '2020-10-01') %>%
  group_by(bucket) %>%
  summarize(sm_sum(cases), sm_sum(deaths), sm_sum(population)) %>%
  mutate(fatality_rate = deaths_sum / cases_sum) %>%
  mutate(infection_rate = cases_sum / population_sum) %>%
  mutate(mortality_rate = deaths_sum / population_sum)

5. Cases and Deaths Lag

Question At the county level, aggregated over each week, what’s the “lag” between deaths and cases? That is, if we look at the number of deaths in one week in the dataset is it most closely correlated with the number of cases in the week in question, one week before, two weeks before, three weeks before, or more? As an optional challenge, try to plot the relationship without resorting to manually copying the numbers (you might need a pivot function here).

covid %>%
 filter(wday(date) == 1) %>%
 group_by(fips, state) %>%
 mutate(new_cases = cases - lag(cases), 
        new_deaths = deaths - lag(deaths)
        ) %>%
 mutate(new_cases_lag_1 = lag(new_cases, 1), 
        new_cases_lag_2 = lag(new_cases, 2),
        new_cases_lag_3 = lag(new_cases, 3),
        new_cases_lag_4 = lag(new_cases, 4),
        new_cases_lag_5 = lag(new_cases, 5)
        ) %>%
 ungroup() %>%
 summarize(
   sm_cor(new_deaths, new_cases),
   sm_cor(new_deaths, new_cases_lag_1),
   sm_cor(new_deaths, new_cases_lag_2),
   sm_cor(new_deaths, new_cases_lag_3),
   sm_cor(new_deaths, new_cases_lag_4),
   sm_cor(new_deaths, new_cases_lag_5)) 
## # A tibble: 1 x 6
##   new_deaths_new_… new_deaths_new_… new_deaths_new_… new_deaths_new_…
##              <dbl>            <dbl>            <dbl>            <dbl>
## 1            0.659            0.701            0.735            0.753
## # … with 2 more variables: new_deaths_new_cases_lag_4_cor <dbl>,
## #   new_deaths_new_cases_lag_5_cor <dbl>

This dataset looks at the correlation values between the new cases and the new deaths for each week. By this graph, it can be seen that the lag between cases and deaths is between 3-4 weeks.

covid %>%
  inner_join(demog, by = c('fips', 'state')) %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)) %>%
  filter(wday == "Monday") %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(sm_sum(cases), sm_sum(deaths)) %>%
  mutate(new_cases = cases_sum- lag(cases_sum)) %>%
  mutate(new_deaths = deaths_sum - lag(deaths_sum)) %>%
  ggplot() + 
    geom_line(aes(x = date, y= new_cases), color = "blue") +
    geom_line(aes(x = date, y = new_deaths), color = "red") +
    scale_y_log10() +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "month", date_labels = "%B", date_minor_breaks = "month") + 
    labs(title = "The Delay Between Covid Deaths and Cases", subtitle = "Blue Represents New Cases, Red Represents New Deaths", x = "Date", y = "New Cases/New Deaths")
## Warning: Removed 1 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

## Warning: Removed 1 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

The red line is slightly behind the blue line by roughly 2-3 weeks. The lowest amount of new cases per day was in mid June and the lowest amount of new deaths per day was in early July. The highest amount of new cases per day was in mid July and the highest amount of new deaths per day was in early August.
